              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Who Speaks for the Seekers</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=1591"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=1591"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=808">Matthew "MattJ" Jensen</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 808 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Maybe this is a rant to some degree, but a challenge was placed on the listserve for someone to set down game-play reasons why the errata on seekers shouldn't have been issued. Here's my attempt. Check out the errata in the latest CRD before reading.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Speaking for the Seekers -<br>
<br>
Greg Anderson issued a challenge on the listserve for someone to give specific game-play reasons why the errata on seekers should be rolled back and reversed. Here's a few reasons - some game-play and others not - to why I think this errata shouldn't have happened the way it did.<br>
<br>
1. It goes against Decipher's standing policy on Errata - Decipher has always prided itself on making a CCG that is not filled with errata and banned cards. In the past, they have been very cautious in striking changes to cards, usually waiting to see if it is just a trend or what not. Decipher has even published that they are loathe to issue errata unless the state of the game makes it so that every player has to specifically tailor their decks to match the deck based around such suspect cards. When was the last time you were putting together a deck and thought, &quot;Geez, I didn't take seekers into account!&quot; Never. Pre-Errate Operatives, Hidden Base choke-style, Astroid Sanctuary are true examples of when errata is necessary, not Seekers.<br>
<br>
2. Seekers are not game winners - By themselves, Seekers are not the best strategy for card efficiency. They can't force drain and can't stop the opponent from force draining. Even when they are effective they are generally a one-for-one force loss. Sure, a main or a scrub is taken out, but so is the Seeker. While a deck set around Attark and Velken can change that to a degree, you are then decreasing your deck efficiency because then you will have 5-15 automated weapons that, as stated, won't directly win you a game.<br>
<br>
3. This punishes newer players - I've heard people comment that we shouldn't worry about the newbies using the seekers. Well, the fact is, some newer players are forced to use them. They even find it cool that perchance when I throw down one of the three EPP Lukes in my deck that they might be able to take me down with it. They just like it. Recently I've introduced a close friend who's 28 years old to the game and he still gets a kick out of throwing a Seeker down here and there. Does it win him games? No. Does it give him a sense of balance and possible triumph against my collection of several years? You betcha.<br>
<br>
4. Single character-based decks will find a way around it - While I can see that the new There Is Good In Him objective would be royally screwed if Jedi Luke was taken out, there are other decks that suffer the same situation and have managed to find ways around it. Profit decks are still extremely popular even though I have seen a few Han Seekers come out. They are usually dispatched with quickly or the player is smart enough to pack multiple Hans to overcome this and other contingencies. RTP decks pack more than one Leia, even with the new Prisoner persona. The list can go on. Granted this might be harder to do with a Jedi Luke and his ultra-rare status, but can you plan around losing him? If you want to succeed you had better!<br>
<br>
5. Seekers have never been the speediest of devils - A big draw back to Seekers is that they don't get up and running very easily. There is not quick deploy card that sets up Seekers. It's not like Uncontrollable Fury where you can play The Signal to get it and zap Vader from the get go. This is why we don't see them as valid response to single character based decks.  Even if you get them out, you generally have to deploy them to an unoccupied site and can't move immediately. This allows the opponent a chance to see it coming and move away through any number of ways. Seekers unfortunately &quot;seek&quot; after people slowly and don't have much of a chance unless the character gets trapped somehow.<br>
<br>
6. Seeker decks are not focused - A successful Seeker deck would have to carry multiples of each type to be effective in a tournament setting. If not there is no way for success. Being this diverse makes it that much more difficult to reliably pull the one type of seeker you need to take out a TIGIH, Profit or RTP deck. If a player &quot;metas&quot; his Seeker deck against a TIGIH deck, pray that he doesn't run into my RTP deck! Let's just say he doesn't stand a chance in a tournament.<br>
<br>
7. This move can be interpreted as a protection for Ultra-Rares - I believe a weighty portion of the decision to the Seeker Errata can be related to the desire to protect the ultra-rare Jedi Luke. Players are going bonkers trying to get this card. Some are successful and others not so. Decipher itself touts this card as having &quot;the biggest numbers in the game.&quot; They based an objective specifically and solely around this card (a mistake imho). It is a great card. And wouldn't it just be spanky if a scrub just happens to throw out a Luke Seeker first turn and turns this glorious end-game objective and an ultra-rare card everyone is clamoring for into so much wasted cardboard. Decipher is right to think that the off-chance that a Seeker hits Jedi Luke would undo their object and be a pooh-pooh of a game. Why didn't they  react this way to the threat of what Out Of Commission could do to a Vader lost to first turn to Visage in Vader-heavy Hunt Down deck? Them's the breaks. However, when players are struggling just to get the Ultra-Rare Luke (Some price estimates have went as high as $100 as a single or 10 boxes as a whole. Personally I think that's insane!) to just have the requirements play the objective, a cheesy and lucky play of an early Luke Seeker isn't even something to chuckle about.<br>
<br>
So there's a list for you. Comment away on it and you tell me why Seekers were issued errata. You can't honestly say it was for the general threat they held to the continuity of the game. So for once I issue a challenge to Decipher to eat crow, believe that we as players can take care of a rogue Seeker deck, and reverse this errata that is a waste of time.<br>
<br>
Matt Jensen<br>
 </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=1591"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=1591"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=1591" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
